    <h1>Fast facts</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201108/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-11-08"><time>2020-11-08</time></a>
        - <span>INVEST</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>THE CHAIR­MAN</p>
    <p>Mr Ravi Thakran is chair­man and man­ag­ing di­rec­tor, The GCC Asia Growth Fund, and chair­man and CEO, As­pi­ra­tional Con­sumer Life­style Corp, US. He is 57 years old.</p>
    <p>He was un­til last month group chair­man of LVMH South and South-east Asia and Aus­tralia/ New Zealand. He was also chair­man emer­i­tus of L Cat­ter­ton Asia and its pre­de­ces­sor fund, L Cap­i­tal Asia.</p>
    <p>Over two decades at LVMH, po­si­tions he held in­cluded group pres­i­dent of watches and jew­ellery Asia-Pa­cific, pres­i­dent of Sephora Asia and Aus­tralia, group pres­i­dent of LVMH South and South-east Asia, Aus­tralia and Mid­dle East since 2007.</p>
    <p>Mr Thakran is also di­rec­tor on var­i­ous bod­ies glob­ally in­clud­ing King­dom of Saudi Ara­bia Fed­eral Com­mis­sion on Fash­ion, Sin­ga­pore Tourism Board, Save Rhino Project South Africa and In­dia Par­ti­tion Mu­seum.</p>
    <p>Prior to his time at LVMH, he held se­nior man­age­ment po­si­tions at the Swatch Group, Nike and Tata Group, based in var­i­ous global lo­ca­tions.</p>
    <p>Mr Thakran was ed­u­cated at Jin­dal Pub­lic School, New Delhi,</p>
    <p>Col­lege of Vet­eri­nary Sciences, Haryana Agri­cul­tural Univer­sity, and holds an MBA from the In­dian In­sti­tute of Man­age­ment, Ahmed­abad.</p>
    <p>Mr Thakran and his artist-cu­ra­tor wife Holly Turner are pro­mot­ers of street art. He has two boys from a pre­vi­ous mar­riage.</p>
    <p>THE COM­PANY</p>
    <p>As­pi­ra­tional Con­sumer Life­style Corp is a newly in­cor­po­rated blank cheque com­pany based in Sin­ga­pore. The com­pany raised more than US$250 mil­lion (S$337 mil­lion) in its ini­tial pub­lic of­fer­ing and has been listed on the New York Stock Ex­change since Sept 23.</p>
    <p>The US$500 mil­lion GCC Asia Growth Fund will tar­get younger com­pa­nies in South-east Asia, In­dia and, par­tic­u­larly, the Mid­dle East, that have at least US$100 mil­lion in rev­enue and a pos­i­tive Ebitda (earn­ings be­fore in­ter­est, taxes, de­pre­ci­a­tion, and amor­ti­sa­tion) of US$10 mil­lion.</p>
    <p>Sep­a­rately, he in­tends to launch a sec­ond pri­vate eq­uity fund called Asia 3.0, with a tar­geted war chest of US$1 bil­lion to US$1.5 bil­lion. It will fo­cus on ma­ture com­pa­nies in Ja­pan, China, South-east Asia and Aus­tralia.</p>


